<br>
Think about it for a second.  If someone does not have a belief in 'sin' (transgression against some supreme entity or it's 'laws') because they do not believe such an entity exists, then it is kind of pointless to argue whether something is or is not a 'sin', isn't it?  It becomes a nonsequitur.  But, to be fair, can you state your argument without invoking religious faith or the word 'believe'?  If so, I would like to hear it.<br>
<br>
And it's pointless, in any case, to argue whether something like homosexuality is 'perverse', anyway.<br>
The very question is leading in nature, and people's responses to it are going to be emotionally, not rationally, based.<br>
<br>
I for one could not care less what other people think about my own or anyone else's sexual orientation, save where it becomes a human/legal rights issue.  *People* (regardless of their sexual, religious, or ethnic orientation, as well as their race, gender, or ability) should have the right to the same legal protections, of fair housing, employment, freedom from harassment, and the freedom to choose their families and designate their heirs.  (In case anyone is wondering, this last statement also means that I personally support the rights of the tens of thousands of religious polygamists in southern Utah and northern Arizona to their plural marriages, provided all parties are of the age of consent). <br>
<br>
If you want to say that you *believe* that homosexuality is a 'sin', that is your right.  If you decide to act on your beliefs and petition your government to legislate that equal rights are *not* granted to homosexuals, then that is also your right.  But to those who travel that path, just remember that your right to swing your fist ends where my face begins... <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
Regards,<br>
Nydia Ywalmoriel<br>
Autonomous Collective<br>
<br>
And to the rediculous example involving an animal: Animals cannot give consent, which is part of the reason we have animal cruelty laws.  A sexual act involving two consenting adults, and one involving *any* party who cannot give consent (including minors, and the incapacitated) are two completely different things...<br>
